05136nmm a2200889Ia 9781479861217DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814798612177 a10.18574/nyu/9781479861217.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)681147  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0840002bisacsh1 aCurtis IV, Edward E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMuslim American Politics and the Future of US Democracy /cEdward E. Curtis IV. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Political Assimilation of Muslim Americans -- t2. The Nation of Islam and the Cold War Liberal Consensus -- t3. Malcolm X and the Islamic Politics of Global Black Liberation -- t4. The Transnational Ethics of Four Muslim American Women in Jordan -- t5. Blood Sacrifice and the Myth of the Fallen Muslim Soldier in US Presidential Elections after 9/11 -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReveals the important role of Muslim Americans in American politics Since the 1950s, and especially in the post-9/11 era, Muslim Americans have played outsized roles in US politics, sometimes as political dissidents and sometimes as political insiders. However, more than at any other moment in history, Muslim Americans now stand at the symbolic center of US politics and public life. This volume argues that the future of American democracy depends on whether Muslim Americans are able to exercise their political rights as citizens and whether they can find acceptance as social equals. Many believe that, over time, Muslim Americans will be accepted just as other religious minorities have been. Yet Curtis contends that this belief overlooks the real barrier to their full citizenship, which is political rather than cultural. The dominant form of American liberalism has prevented the political assimilation of American Muslims, even while leaders from Eisenhower to Obama have offered rhetorical support for their acceptance. Drawing on examples ranging from the political rhetoric of the Nation of Islam in the 1950s and 1960s to the symbolic use of fallen Muslim American service members in the 2016 election cycle, Curtis shows that the efforts of Muslim Americans to be regarded as full Americans have been going on for decades, yet never with full success. Curtis argues that policies, laws, and political rhetoric concerning Muslim Americans are quintessential American political questions. Debates about freedom of speech and religion, equal justice under law, and the war on terrorism have placed Muslim Americans at the center of public discourse. How Americans decide to view and make policy regarding Muslim Americans will play a large role in what kind of country the United States will become, and whether it will be a country that chooses freedom over fear and justice over prejudice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh  aAndré Carson.  aCold War.  aGamal Abdel Nasser.  aHumayun Khan.  aIslam.  aIslamophobia.  aJordan.  aKareem Khan.  aLinda Sarsour.  aMalcolm X.  aNation of Islam.  aUnited States.  aactivism.  aanticommunism.  aassimilation.  acapitalism.  ademocracy.  adiscrimination.  adissent.  aelection.  aforeign policy.  ahajj.  aimmigration.  aliberalism.  anationalism.  apolitics.  aracial integration.  aracism.  asocialism.  awar on terror.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479861217.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978